<!-- SECTION 6: API & AUTHENTICATION -->
<!-- ============================================================ -->
<div class="cat-section mb-2" id="sec-api">
  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 py-5">
    <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-gradient-to-b from-purple-500 to-violet-400 rounded-full"></div>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white">REST API & Integration</h2>
    <span class="text-xs font-mono text-gray-500 bg-[#1a1a1a] border border-[#333] px-3 py-1 rounded-full">8 Questions</span>
  </div>
  <div class="space-y-3">

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="api" data-diff="mid">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#75</span><span class="diff-badge diff-mid">Mid</span>
        <span class="q-title">What makes a truly RESTful API? Common mistakes Laravel developers make.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <p><strong>RESTful principles:</strong> Stateless, uniform interface, resource-based URLs, correct HTTP verbs and status codes, HATEOAS (links in responses).</p>
        <p><strong>Common mistakes:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Using verbs in URLs: <code>/getUser</code> ❌ → <code>/users/{id}</code> ✅</li>
          <li>Wrong status codes: returning 200 for errors ❌, 422 for validation, 404 for not found, 401 unauthenticated, 403 unauthorized.</li>
          <li>Not versioning the API from day 1.</li>
          <li>Returning HTML instead of JSON on errors.</li>
          <li>Inconsistent response format — always standardize: <code>{data, message, errors}</code>.</li>
          <li>No pagination on collection endpoints.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="api" data-diff="adv">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#76</span><span class="diff-badge diff-adv">Advanced</span>
        <span class="q-title">How do you handle API errors consistently across a Laravel application?</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>// app/Exceptions/Handler.php
public function register(): void {
    $this->renderable(function (ValidationException $e, $request) {
        if ($request->expectsJson()) {
            return response()->json([
                'message' => 'Validation failed',
                'errors'  => $e->errors(),
            ], 422);
        }
    });

    $this->renderable(function (ModelNotFoundException $e, $request) {
        if ($request->expectsJson()) {
            return response()->json(['message' => 'Resource not found'], 404);
        }
    });

    $this->renderable(function (AuthorizationException $e) {
        return response()->json(['message' => 'Forbidden'], 403);
    });
}</pre>
        <p>Centralizing error handling ensures consistent JSON responses for API consumers regardless of where the exception originates.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="api" data-diff="adv">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#77</span><span class="diff-badge diff-adv">Advanced</span>
        <span class="q-title">How do you consume external APIs reliably using Laravel's HTTP client?</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Http;

$response = Http::withToken($this->apiKey)
    ->withHeaders(['X-Custom-Header' => 'value'])
    ->timeout(30)
    ->retry(3, 500, function ($e, $request) {
        return $e instanceof ConnectionException;
    })
    ->post('https://api.example.com/orders', $data);

if ($response->failed()) {
    Log::error('API call failed', ['status' => $response->status(), 'body' => $response->body()]);
    throw new ExternalApiException($response->json('message'));
}

$order = $response->json('data.order');

// Fake in tests
Http::fake([
    'api.example.com/*' => Http::response(['data' => ['order' => [...]]], 200),
]);</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="api" data-diff="mid">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#78</span><span class="diff-badge diff-mid">Mid</span>
        <span class="q-title">How do you implement GraphQL in Laravel? Pros and cons vs REST.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <p>Use the <code>rebing/graphql-laravel</code> or <code>lighthouse-php/lighthouse</code> package. Lighthouse uses schema-first approach with Eloquent auto-resolution.</p>
        <pre># GraphQL schema (Lighthouse)
type Query {
    user(id: ID! @eq): User @find
    users: [User!]! @paginate
}
type User {
    id: ID!
    name: String!
    posts: [Post!]! @hasMany
}</pre>
        <p><strong>GraphQL pros:</strong> Client specifies exact data needs, reduces over/under-fetching, single endpoint, strongly typed.</p>
        <p><strong>GraphQL cons:</strong> Complex caching (no URL-based cache), N+1 still possible (use DataLoader), harder rate limiting, steeper learning curve.</p>
        <p><strong>Use REST for:</strong> Simple APIs, public APIs, when caching is critical. Use GraphQL for: complex frontends with varied data needs, BFF (Backend For Frontend) patterns.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="api" data-diff="mid">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#79</span><span class="diff-badge diff-mid">Mid</span>
        <span class="q-title">Explain how to build idempotent API endpoints in Laravel.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <p>Idempotency: making the same request multiple times produces the same result (no duplicate orders). Critical for payment processing, order creation.</p>
        <pre>// Client sends Idempotency-Key header
class IdempotencyMiddleware {
    public function handle($request, $next) {
        $key = $request->header('Idempotency-Key');
        if (!$key) return $next($request);

        $cached = Cache::get("idempotency:{$key}");
        if ($cached) return response()->json($cached);

        $response = $next($request);
        Cache::put("idempotency:{$key}", $response->getData(), now()->addHours(24));
        return $response;
    }
}</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="api" data-diff="adv">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#80</span><span class="diff-badge diff-adv">Advanced</span>
        <span class="q-title">How do you design microservices with Laravel? How do they communicate?</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Synchronous (REST/HTTP):</strong> Service A calls Service B's API. Simple but creates coupling and cascading failures. Use circuit breakers.</li>
          <li><strong>Asynchronous (Message queues):</strong> Services publish events to RabbitMQ/Kafka/SQS. Other services subscribe. Decoupled, resilient, eventually consistent.</li>
          <li><strong>gRPC:</strong> Binary protocol, strongly typed (Protocol Buffers), 5-10x faster than REST. Use for high-throughput internal services.</li>
        </ul>
        <pre>// Publishing to message bus (using laravel-queue with SQS)
dispatch(new OrderCreatedEvent($order));

// Or direct HTTP with retry
Http::retry(3, 100)->post('http://inventory-service/reserve', [
    'order_id' => $order->id,
    'items'    => $order->items->toArray(),
]);</pre>
        <p>Lumen (Laravel's micro-framework) is ideal for individual microservices needing lightweight footprint.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="api" data-diff="mid">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#81</span><span class="diff-badge diff-mid">Mid</span>
        <span class="q-title">How do you document a Laravel API? (OpenAPI/Swagger)</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <p>Options: <code>darkaonline/l5-swagger</code> (annotations), <code>knuckleswtf/scribe</code> (auto-generates from code), or <code>dedoc/scramble</code> (OpenAPI from code analysis, no annotations needed).</p>
        <pre>// Scribe annotation approach
/**
 * @group Order Management
 * @authenticated
 * @response 200 {"data": {"id": 1, "status": "pending"}}
 * @response 422 {"message": "Validation failed", "errors": {...}}
 */
public function store(StoreOrderRequest $request): OrderResource { ... }</pre>
        <p><strong>Best practice:</strong> Auto-generate from code. Manual documentation gets out of sync. Scribe and Scramble analyze your routes, Form Requests, and Resources to generate accurate docs.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="api" data-diff="adv">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#82</span><span class="diff-badge diff-adv">Advanced</span>
        <span class="q-title">How do you handle API backward compatibility when evolving a public API?</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <ul>
          <li>Additive changes are safe: add new fields, new optional parameters.</li>
          <li>Breaking changes require version bump: removing fields, changing field types, changing auth mechanisms.</li>
          <li>Deprecation period: mark fields as deprecated in documentation, keep them for 6-12 months.</li>
          <li>API Resources as a transformation layer: change internal model without changing API response.</li>
          <li>Sunset headers: <code>Sunset: Sat, 01 Jan 2027 00:00:00 GMT</code> tells clients when v1 dies.</li>
          <li>Changelogs and versioned documentation are essential.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</div>

<!-- ============================================================ -->
<!-- SECTION 7: TESTING & DevOps -->
<!-- ============================================================ -->
<div class="cat-section mb-2" id="sec-testing">
  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 py-5">
    <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-gradient-to-b from-cyan-500 to-teal-400 rounded-full"></div>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white">Testing & DevOps / CI-CD</h2>
    <span class="text-xs font-mono text-gray-500 bg-[#1a1a1a] border border-[#333] px-3 py-1 rounded-full">12 Questions</span>
  </div>
  <div class="space-y-3">

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="testing" data-diff="mid">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#83</span><span class="diff-badge diff-mid">Mid</span>
        <span class="q-title">Explain the difference between Unit Tests, Feature Tests, and Integration Tests in Laravel.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Unit Tests:</strong> Test a single class/method in isolation. No database, no HTTP. Fast. Mock dependencies.</li>
          <li><strong>Feature Tests:</strong> Test full HTTP request/response cycle. Hits routes, controllers, DB (using SQLite in-memory or RefreshDatabase). The most valuable for APIs.</li>
          <li><strong>Integration Tests:</strong> Test interactions between multiple real components. No mocks of internal classes.</li>
        </ul>
        <pre>// Feature Test
class OrderApiTest extends TestCase {
    use RefreshDatabase; // rollback after each test

    public function test_can_place_order() {
        $user = User::factory()->create();
        $product = Product::factory()->inStock()->create();

        $this->actingAs($user)
             ->postJson('/api/orders', ['product_id' => $product->id, 'qty' => 2])
             ->assertCreated()
             ->assertJsonPath('data.status', 'pending');

        $this->assertDatabaseHas('orders', ['user_id' => $user->id]);
    }
}</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="testing" data-diff="adv">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
