    <div class="q-card" data-cat="testing" data-diff="adv">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#87</span><span class="diff-badge diff-adv">Advanced</span>
        <span class="q-title">Explain test-driven development (TDD) workflow in Laravel.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <p>Red → Green → Refactor cycle:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Red:</strong> Write a failing test that describes the desired behavior.</li>
          <li><strong>Green:</strong> Write minimum code to make the test pass.</li>
          <li><strong>Refactor:</strong> Clean up the code while keeping tests green.</li>
        </ul>
        <pre>// 1. Write test first (RED)
public function test_user_can_cancel_order_within_30_minutes() {
    $order = Order::factory()->create(['created_at' => now()->subMinutes(20)]);
    $this->actingAs($order->user)->deleteJson("/api/orders/{$order->id}")
         ->assertOk();
    expect($order->fresh()->status)->toBe('cancelled');
}

// 2. Implement the feature (GREEN)
// 3. Refactor safely</pre>
        <p><strong>Laravel Pest:</strong> Modern, expressive test framework. <code>expect($value)->toBe()</code> syntax. Strongly recommended for 2025+ projects.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="testing" data-diff="adv">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#88</span><span class="diff-badge diff-adv">Advanced</span>
        <span class="q-title">Describe a complete CI/CD pipeline for a Laravel application.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre># .github/workflows/ci.yml
steps:
  - uses: actions/checkout@v4
  - name: Setup PHP
    uses: shivammathur/setup-php@v2
    with: {php-version: '8.3'}
  - run: composer install --no-dev --optimize-autoloader
  - run: cp .env.testing .env && php artisan key:generate
  - name: Run Tests
    run: php artisan test --parallel
  - name: Static Analysis
    run: ./vendor/bin/phpstan analyse
  - name: Deploy (on main branch)
    if: github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'
    run: |
      php artisan down --allow=$DEPLOY_SERVER_IP
      git pull origin main
      composer install --no-dev
      php artisan migrate --force
      php artisan optimize
      php artisan queue:restart
      php artisan up</pre>
        <p>Zero-downtime: use Laravel Envoyer, Deployer, or rolling deploy strategies. Blue-green deployments for critical systems.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="testing" data-diff="mid">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#89</span><span class="diff-badge diff-mid">Mid</span>
        <span class="q-title">How do you Dockerize a Laravel application for production?</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre># Dockerfile
FROM php:8.3-fpm-alpine
WORKDIR /app
COPY --chown=www-data:www-data . .
RUN composer install --no-dev --optimize-autoloader
RUN php artisan config:cache route:cache view:cache

# docker-compose.yml
services:
  app:     {build: ., volumes: ['.:/app']}
  nginx:   {image: nginx, depends_on: [app]}
  mysql:   {image: mysql:8}
  redis:   {image: redis:alpine}
  queue:   {build: ., command: 'php artisan queue:work redis'}
  horizon: {build: ., command: 'php artisan horizon'}</pre>
        <p>Use <strong>Laravel Sail</strong> for local development (official Docker environment). For production, use multi-stage Docker builds to keep images small.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="testing" data-diff="adv">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#90</span><span class="diff-badge diff-adv">Advanced</span>
        <span class="q-title">How do you handle zero-downtime deployments for Laravel?</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Atomic deploys (symlink strategy):</strong> New release in a new directory. Swap symlink atomically when ready. Envoyer/Deployer do this.</li>
          <li><strong>Database migrations:</strong> Must be backward compatible. Deploy code that works with OLD schema, then run migration, then remove old compatibility code in next deploy.</li>
          <li><strong>Queue restart:</strong> <code>php artisan queue:restart</code> gracefully finishes current job then reloads worker.</li>
          <li><strong>Maintenance mode with <code>--secret</code>:</strong> <code>php artisan down --secret=token</code> lets you bypass with <code>?secret=token</code>.</li>
          <li><strong>Blue-green deployment:</strong> Two identical environments. Route traffic to the new one after deploy succeeds.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="testing" data-diff="mid">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#91</span><span class="diff-badge diff-mid">Mid</span>
        <span class="q-title">What is Laravel Telescope and Horizon? When to use each?</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <p><strong>Laravel Telescope:</strong> Debug assistant. Monitors requests, jobs, queries, cache, mail, notifications, exceptions, log messages. Web dashboard at <code>/telescope</code>. Use in staging/development — too much overhead for production (use sampling or disable).</p>
        <p><strong>Laravel Horizon:</strong> Redis queue management dashboard. Monitors throughput, wait times, failed jobs, job counts. Configure supervisor-like queue workers in code. Use in production — lightweight, built for production monitoring.</p>
        <pre>// horizon.php — define worker pools
'production' => [
    'supervisor-1' => [
        'connection' => 'redis',
        'queue'      => ['high', 'default', 'low'],
        'balance'    => 'auto',
        'minProcesses' => 2,
        'maxProcesses' => 10,
    ],
],</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="testing" data-diff="adv">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#92</span><span class="diff-badge diff-adv">Advanced</span>
        <span class="q-title">How do you perform load testing and benchmark a Laravel API?</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>k6:</strong> JavaScript-based load testing tool. Define scenarios, virtual users, thresholds.</li>
          <li><strong>Apache Bench (ab):</strong> Quick: <code>ab -n 1000 -c 50 http://api.example.com/users</code></li>
          <li><strong>Artillery:</strong> YAML-based, good for complex scenarios.</li>
          <li><strong>Gatling:</strong> JVM-based, excellent reports.</li>
        </ul>
        <pre>// k6 test
import http from 'k6/http';
export let options = {
  stages: [
    { duration: '1m', target: 50 },  // ramp up
    { duration: '3m', target: 50 },  // sustain
    { duration: '1m', target: 0 },   // ramp down
  ],
  thresholds: { http_req_duration: ['p(95)<500'] }, // 95% under 500ms
};
export default function() {
  http.get('https://api.example.com/products');
}</pre>
