    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#95</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">What is Big O notation? Give the complexity of common operations.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <p>Big O describes the worst-case time/space complexity as input size grows.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>O(1)</strong> — Constant: array access by index, hash table lookup</li>
          <li><strong>O(log n)</strong> — Logarithmic: binary search, balanced BST operations</li>
          <li><strong>O(n)</strong> — Linear: linear search, traversing array/linked list</li>
          <li><strong>O(n log n)</strong> — Merge sort, quick sort (avg), heap sort</li>
          <li><strong>O(n²)</strong> — Bubble sort, insertion sort, nested loops over same data</li>
          <li><strong>O(2ⁿ)</strong> — Exponential: naive Fibonacci, power set</li>
          <li><strong>O(n!)</strong> — Factorial: permutations, travelling salesman brute force</li>
        </ul>
        <pre>// PHP practical example
$arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
$arr[2];           // O(1)
in_array(5, $arr); // O(n) — searches linearly
sort($arr);        // O(n log n)</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#96</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Implement a binary search in PHP. What's its time complexity?</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>function binarySearch(array $arr, int $target): int {
    $low  = 0;
    $high = count($arr) - 1;

    while ($low <= $high) {
        $mid = intdiv($low + $high, 2);
        if ($arr[$mid] === $target) return $mid;
        if ($arr[$mid] < $target) $low  = $mid + 1;
        else                      $high = $mid - 1;
    }
    return -1; // not found
}

$arr = [1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 15, 20];
echo binarySearch($arr, 7);  // returns 3
echo binarySearch($arr, 6);  // returns -1</pre>
        <p><strong>Time:</strong> O(log n) — halves search space each iteration. <strong>Space:</strong> O(1) iterative, O(log n) recursive (call stack). <strong>Requirement:</strong> Array MUST be sorted.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#97</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Implement a Stack and Queue in PHP. Where are they used in Laravel?</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>// Stack (LIFO)
class Stack {
    private array $items = [];
    public function push($item): void { $this->items[] = $item; }
    public function pop() { return array_pop($this->items); }
    public function peek() { return end($this->items); }
    public function isEmpty(): bool { return empty($this->items); }
}

// Queue (FIFO)
class Queue {
    private array $items = [];
    public function enqueue($item): void { $this->items[] = $item; }
    public function dequeue() { return array_shift($this->items); }
    public function isEmpty(): bool { return empty($this->items); }
}</pre>
        <p><strong>Stack in Laravel:</strong> Middleware pipeline processes inward as a stack. Call stack for exception handling.</p>
        <p><strong>Queue in Laravel:</strong> Job queue system (Redis queues are FIFO). Request pipeline is queue-like.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#98</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Find the Two Sum problem — find two numbers that add to a target.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>// Brute force — O(n²)
function twoSumBrute(array $nums, int $target): array {
    for ($i = 0; $i < count($nums); $i++) {
        for ($j = $i + 1; $j < count($nums); $j++) {
            if ($nums[$i] + $nums[$j] === $target) return [$i, $j];
        }
    }
    return [];
}

// Optimal — O(n) using hash map
function twoSum(array $nums, int $target): array {
    $seen = []; // value => index
    foreach ($nums as $i => $num) {
        $complement = $target - $num;
        if (isset($seen[$complement])) {
            return [$seen[$complement], $i];
        }
        $seen[$num] = $i;
    }
    return [];
}

twoSum([2, 7, 11, 15], 9); // [0, 1] — 2+7=9</pre>
        <p><strong>Real-world application:</strong> Finding discount combinations, matching payment amounts.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#99</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Implement a Linked List in PHP and explain when to use it vs arrays.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>class ListNode {
    public function __construct(
        public int $val = 0,
        public ?ListNode $next = null
    ) {}
}

class LinkedList {
    private ?ListNode $head = null;

    public function prepend(int $val): void {
        $this->head = new ListNode($val, $this->head);
    }

    public function toArray(): array {
        $result = [];
        $current = $this->head;
        while ($current !== null) {
            $result[] = $current->val;
            $current = $current->next;
        }
        return $result;
    }
}

// Reverse a linked list — classic interview question
function reverseList(?ListNode $head): ?ListNode {
    $prev = null;
    $current = $head;
    while ($current !== null) {
        $next = $current->next;
        $current->next = $prev;
        $prev = $current;
        $current = $next;
    }
    return $prev;
}</pre>
        <p><strong>Linked List vs Array:</strong> LL: O(1) insert/delete at head, O(n) random access. Array: O(1) random access, O(n) insert/delete at start. In PHP, arrays handle most use cases. LL useful for queues and when frequent insertion at head is needed.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#100</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Explain recursion vs iteration. Implement Fibonacci with memoization in PHP.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>// Naive recursion — O(2^n) — extremely slow
function fib(int $n): int {
    if ($n <= 1) return $n;
    return fib($n - 1) + fib($n - 2);
}

// With memoization — O(n) time, O(n) space
function fibMemo(int $n, array &$memo = []): int {
    if ($n <= 1) return $n;
    if (isset($memo[$n])) return $memo[$n];
    return $memo[$n] = fibMemo($n-1, $memo) + fibMemo($n-2, $memo);
}

// Bottom-up DP — O(n) time, O(1) space (best)
function fibDP(int $n): int {
    if ($n <= 1) return $n;
    [$prev, $curr] = [0, 1];
    for ($i = 2; $i <= $n; $i++) {
        [$prev, $curr] = [$curr, $prev + $curr];
    }
    return $curr;
}

echo fibDP(50); // instant!</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#101</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Implement QuickSort in PHP and explain its best/worst/average complexity.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>function quickSort(array $arr): array {
    if (count($arr) <= 1) return $arr;

    $pivot = $arr[array_key_first($arr)];
    $left  = $right = [];

    for ($i = 1; $i < count($arr); $i++) {
        if ($arr[$i] <= $pivot) $left[]  = $arr[$i];
        else                    $right[] = $arr[$i];
    }

    return array_merge(quickSort($left), [$pivot], quickSort($right));
}

print_r(quickSort([3, 6, 8, 10, 1, 2, 1]));</pre>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Best case:</strong> O(n log n) — pivot always splits array evenly</li>
          <li><strong>Average:</strong> O(n log n)</li>
          <li><strong>Worst case:</strong> O(n²) — pivot is always smallest/largest (sorted array + first element pivot)</li>
          <li><strong>Space:</strong> O(log n) call stack</li>
          <li>PHP's native <code>sort()</code> uses a combination of QuickSort, HeapSort, InsertionSort (IntroSort).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#102</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Implement a Hash Map (dictionary) and explain collision resolution.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>// PHP arrays ARE hash maps — O(1) average lookup
$cache = [];
$cache['user:1'] = ['name' => 'Alice', 'role' => 'admin'];
$cache['user:2'] = ['name' => 'Bob',   'role' => 'user'];

// Practical: frequency counter
function findDuplicates(array $arr): array {
    $freq = [];
    foreach ($arr as $item) {
        $freq[$item] = ($freq[$item] ?? 0) + 1;
    }
    return array_keys(array_filter($freq, fn($count) => $count > 1));
}

findDuplicates([1, 2, 3, 2, 4, 3]); // [2, 3]</pre>
        <p><strong>Collision resolution:</strong> Chaining (each bucket is a linked list) vs Open addressing (probe to next slot). PHP uses a combination with hash tables that store doubly-linked lists per bucket.</p>
        <p><strong>Real-world in Laravel:</strong> Cache keys, route lookup table, Collection <code>keyBy()</code>, config array.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#103</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Find the maximum subarray sum (Kadane's Algorithm) in PHP.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>function maxSubarraySum(array $nums): int {
    $maxSum     = $nums[0];
    $currentSum = $nums[0];

    for ($i = 1; $i < count($nums); $i++) {
        // Either extend previous subarray or start fresh
        $currentSum = max($nums[$i], $currentSum + $nums[$i]);
        $maxSum     = max($maxSum, $currentSum);
    }

    return $maxSum;
}

maxSubarraySum([-2, 1, -3, 4, -1, 2, 1, -5, 4]); // 6 (subarray: [4,-1,2,1])</pre>
        <p><strong>Time:</strong> O(n), <strong>Space:</strong> O(1). Classic dynamic programming problem. Real-world: finding best time window for sales data, max profit period.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#104</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Implement a valid parentheses checker using a Stack in PHP.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>function isValid(string $s): bool {
    $stack = [];
    $map = [')' => '(', ']' => '[', '}' => '{'];

    foreach (str_split($s) as $char) {
        if (in_array($char, ['(', '[', '{'])) {
            $stack[] = $char;           // push opening bracket
        } elseif (isset($map[$char])) {
            if (empty($stack) || array_pop($stack) !== $map[$char]) {
                return false;           // mismatched closing bracket
            }
        }
    }

    return empty($stack);               // stack should be empty if valid
}

isValid("()[]{}");   // true
isValid("([{}])");   // true
isValid("(]");       // false
isValid("{[}]");     // false</pre>
        <p><strong>Complexity:</strong> O(n) time, O(n) space. Directly applicable in: JSON/XML parsing, code linting, template engine validation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#105</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Find the first non-repeating character in a string — O(n) solution.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>function firstNonRepeating(string $s): string {
    $freq = [];
    // Pass 1: count frequencies
    foreach (str_split($s) as $char) {
        $freq[$char] = ($freq[$char] ?? 0) + 1;
    }
    // Pass 2: find first with count = 1
    foreach (str_split($s) as $char) {
        if ($freq[$char] === 1) return $char;
    }
    return '';
}

firstNonRepeating("leetcode");     // "l"
firstNonRepeating("aabb");         // ""
firstNonRepeating("abcabc");       // ""
firstNonRepeating("aababc");       // "c"</pre>
        <p><strong>Time:</strong> O(n), <strong>Space:</strong> O(k) where k is alphabet size. Real-world: de-duplication, log analysis, user input parsing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#106</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Detect a cycle in a linked list (Floyd's algorithm) — applicable to Laravel queue loops.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>function hasCycle(?ListNode $head): bool {
    $slow = $head;
    $fast = $head;

    while ($fast !== null && $fast->next !== null) {
        $slow = $slow->next;           // moves 1 step
        $fast = $fast->next->next;     // moves 2 steps

        if ($slow === $fast) return true; // cycle detected
    }

    return false; // no cycle
}
</pre>
        <p><strong>Floyd's Tortoise & Hare:</strong> Two pointers at different speeds. If cycle exists, fast will lap slow. O(n) time, O(1) space (no extra data structures).</p>
        <p><strong>Real-world relevance:</strong> Detecting circular dependencies in service containers, infinite redirect loops detection, circular references in data structures.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#107</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Implement BFS and DFS for a graph. Real-world applications in web dev.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>// BFS — Level by level (uses Queue)
function bfs(array $graph, int $start): array {
    $visited = [];
    $queue   = [$start];
    while (!empty($queue)) {
        $node = array_shift($queue);    // dequeue
        if (in_array($node, $visited)) continue;
        $visited[] = $node;
        foreach ($graph[$node] ?? [] as $neighbor) {
            $queue[] = $neighbor;       // enqueue neighbors
        }
    }
    return $visited;
}

// DFS — Depth first (uses Stack / recursion)
function dfs(array $graph, int $node, array &$visited = []): array {
    $visited[] = $node;
    foreach ($graph[$node] ?? [] as $neighbor) {
        if (!in_array($neighbor, $visited)) {
            dfs($graph, $neighbor, $visited);
        }
    }
    return $visited;
}</pre>
        <p><strong>BFS uses:</strong> Shortest path (fewer hops), social network friend suggestions, web crawler level-by-level. <strong>DFS uses:</strong> Detecting cycles, topological sort, solving mazes, category tree traversal.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#108</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Implement merge sort and explain why it's preferred over quicksort in some cases.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>function mergeSort(array $arr): array {
    $n = count($arr);
    if ($n <= 1) return $arr;

    $mid   = intdiv($n, 2);
    $left  = mergeSort(array_slice($arr, 0, $mid));
    $right = mergeSort(array_slice($arr, $mid));

    return merge($left, $right);
}

function merge(array $left, array $right): array {
    $result = [];
    $i = $j = 0;
    while ($i < count($left) && $j < count($right)) {
        if ($left[$i] <= $right[$j]) $result[] = $left[$i++];
        else                          $result[] = $right[$j++];
    }
    return array_merge($result, array_slice($left, $i), array_slice($right, $j));
}</pre>
        <p><strong>Merge Sort:</strong> Always O(n log n) — stable, predictable. Better for linked lists and external sorting (huge files that don't fit in RAM). QuickSort is usually faster in practice for in-memory arrays but has O(n²) worst case.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#109</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">Implement LRU Cache (Least Recently Used) — used in Laravel's cache strategies.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <pre>class LRUCache {
    private array $cache = [];
    private int $capacity;

    public function __construct(int $capacity) {
        $this->capacity = $capacity;
    }

    public function get(int $key): int {
        if (!isset($this->cache[$key])) return -1;
        // Move to end (most recently used)
        $value = $this->cache[$key];
        unset($this->cache[$key]);
        $this->cache[$key] = $value;
        return $value;
    }

    public function put(int $key, int $value): void {
        if (isset($this->cache[$key])) unset($this->cache[$key]);
        elseif (count($this->cache) >= $this->capacity) {
            // Remove least recently used (first element)
            reset($this->cache);
            unset($this->cache[key($this->cache)]);
        }
        $this->cache[$key] = $value;
    }
}

$lru = new LRUCache(3);
$lru->put(1, 1); $lru->put(2, 2); $lru->put(3, 3);
$lru->get(1);    // access 1, now LRU order: [2,3,1]
$lru->put(4, 4); // evicts 2 (LRU)
$lru->get(2);    // returns -1 (evicted)</pre>
        <p>Redis implements LRU eviction natively. This is exactly how <code>CACHE_MAX_SIZE</code> and Redis <code>maxmemory-policy allkeys-lru</code> works.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-cat="dsa" data-diff="dsa">
      <div class="q-header" onclick="toggle(this)">
        <span class="q-num">#110</span><span class="diff-badge diff-dsa">DSA</span>
        <span class="q-title">What is dynamic programming? Solve the "Climbing Stairs" problem.</span>
        <svg class="q-chevron" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="q-body">
        <p>DP solves optimization problems by breaking them into overlapping subproblems and storing results (memoization or tabulation) to avoid redundant computation.</p>
        <pre>// Problem: n stairs, can climb 1 or 2 steps. How many ways to reach top?
// Same as Fibonacci!

function climbStairs(int $n): int {
    if ($n <= 2) return $n;
    $dp = array_fill(0, $n + 1, 0);
    $dp[1] = 1; // 1 way to climb 1 stair
    $dp[2] = 2; // 2 ways to climb 2 stairs (1+1 or 2)
    for ($i = 3; $i <= $n; $i++) {
        $dp[$i] = $dp[$i-1] + $dp[$i-2];
    }
    return $dp[$n];
}
// O(n) time, O(n) space
// Can reduce to O(1) space same as Fibonacci DP

climbStairs(5);  // 8 ways</pre>
        <p><strong>DP patterns:</strong> Optimal substructure + overlapping subproblems. Real-world: route optimization, pricing algorithms, text diff (git), sequence alignment.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

